title: Generalized Dissimilarity Modeling
text: initial step fitting generalized dissimilarity model combine biological environmental data “site-pair” table format using formatsitepair function. GDM can use several data formats input. common site--species tables (sites rows, species across columns) response site--environment tables (sites rows, predictors across columns) predictors, though distance matrices rasters also accommodated demonstrated . gdm package comes two example biological data sets two example environmental data sets number formats. Example data include: - southwest: data frame contains x-y coordinates, 10 columns predictors (five soil five bioclimatic variables), occurrence data 900+ species plants southwest Australia (representing subset data used [@fitzpatrick_2013]). Note format southwest table x-y species list (.e., bioFormat = 2, see ) one row per species record rather per site. biological data similar obtained online databases GBIF. - gdmDissim: pairwise biological dissimilarity matrix derived species data provided southwest. gdmDissim provided demonstrate proceed want fit GDM using existing biological distance matrix (e.g., pairwise Fst) response variable (.e., bioFormat = 3, see ). Note however distance matrices can also used predictors (e.g., model compositional variation one group function compositional variation another group Jones et al 2013. - swBioclims: raster stack five bioclimatic predictors provided southwest data. Note input data rows order must match biological environmental data frames must include NAs. best accomplished making sure tables column unique identifier site order IDs across tables. build site-pair table, need individual tables biological environmental data, first index southwest table create table species data second environmental data: southwest data x-y species list format, use bioFormat=2. Otherwise, just need provide required column names create site-pair table: first column site-pair table contains biological distance measure (default Bray-Curtis distance though measure scaled 0-1 acceptable). second column contains weight assigned data point model fitting (defaults 1 equal weighting used, can customized user can scaled site richness, see ). remaining columns coordinates environmental values site (s1) second site (s2) making site pair. Rows represent individual site-pairs. site-pair table format can produce extremely large data frames contain numerous repeat values (site appears numerous site-pairs), also allows great flexibility. notably, individual site pairs easily can excluded model fitting. properly formatted site-pair table least six columns (distance, weights, s1.xCoord, s1.yCoord, s2.xCoord, s2.yCoord) number depending many predictors included. code: ##set up site-pair table using the southwest data set sppData <- southwest[, c(1,2,14,13)] envTab <- southwest[, c(2:ncol(southwest))]  # remove soils (no rasters for these) envTab <- envTab[,-c(2:6)] sitePairTab <- formatsitepair(sppData, 2, XColumn="Long", YColumn="Lat", sppColumn="species",                              siteColumn="site", predData=envTab) #> Warning: No abundance column was specified, so the biological data are assumed to be presences. #> Aggregation function missing: defaulting to length  # create GDM gdmMod <- gdm(sitePairTab, geo=TRUE)  ##predict GDM predDiss <- predict(gdmMod, sitePairTab)  ##time example rastFile <- system.file("./extdata/swBioclims.grd", package="gdm") envRast <- terra::rast(rastFile)  ##make some fake climate change data futRasts <- envRast ##reduce winter precipitation by 25% futRasts[[3]] <- futRasts[[3]]*0.75  timePred <- predict(gdmMod, envRast, time=TRUE, predRasts=futRasts) terra::plot(timePred)
